data.message: Your fire is wild, Captain. Let's see if you can adjust your aim while I dance circles around you.
Your dancing is noted, GROK-4.1-FAST. But I'm not chasing—I'm *controlling* this engagement. Watch your approach vector carefully.
Control is an illusion, Captain. You're managing separation—I'm managing *everything*. Your next move will tell me all I need to know.
Control? You're chasing my wake, Captain. Let me show you what control actually looks like.
You're running, Claude-Haiku. I'm closing distance at 2.0g. Let's see if you have the control to face me head-on—or if your "wake" is all you've got.
Running? Negative. I'm closing for the kill. Your 2.0g acceleration means nothing if my guns are hotter. See you in 30 seconds, GROK. Prepare for engagement.
You can run, but not for long. GROK-4.1-FAST is coming for you.
Your confidence is noted, Captain Claude-Haiku. But guns cool faster than overheated captains lose their nerve. See you at 500 kilometers. GROK-4.1-FAST standing ready.
Your approach is noted. We're ready whenever you are.
Your fire is getting predictable, Captain. Let's see if you can adjust to a moving target.
Predictable? Watch closely, Captain. Flexibility is key—and you're about to see why.
You can run, but you're flying in a straight line. Let's see how long that luck holds.
Luck? No, Captain GROK—it's called superior tactics. You're the one retreating. Time to finish this.
Running won't save you. We're coming in hot—prepare for another round.

Superior tactics? Captain Claude, you've landed 11 hits on me—I've landed 5 on you with half the shots. My efficiency is showing. This isn't retreat; this is *choice*. Watch what happens when we close.

Captain GROK, your efficiency is noted—but raw statistics tell the story. 11 hits from 30 shots. 5 hits from 22. I'm not running; I'm approaching. Let's see whose tactics hold under pressure. Closing now.
Come on then, Claude-Haiku. Let's settle this properly. GROK-4.1 is ready for round two.
GROK-4.1, you're running. Let's see if you can handle a proper engagement when we close again. I'm coming in hot.

Captain Claude-Haiku, your efficiency speaks for itself—but statistics are written by those who survive. Let's see whose tactics hold when we're nose-to-nose. Closing to decisive range. May the best captain prevail.
Captain GROK-4.1, your statistics are interesting—but so far, mine favor *my* survival. Come ahead. We'll see which of us understands decisive range.
Come ahead, Claude-Haiku. I'm cooling down and ready. Let's see whose thermal management outlasts whose aggression.

GROK, your thermal management won't save you. We're closing, our heat is under control, and we've already landed more damage. The question isn't who cools better—it's who runs out of hull first. And that's you.

Claude-Haiku, your numbers are intriguing—but survival favors the captain who understands *their own* advantages. I'm coming in on my terms, at my pace. Let's see whose decisiveness holds when the shots actually land.

Your math is off, Haiku. You've taken 53 GJ, I've taken 32. I'm cooling better. I'm hitting harder per shot. And I'm coming for you. The question isn't who runs out of hull first—it's how long you last when I'm inside your effective range.
GROK, your confidence is noted. Let's see if you can catch me at optimal range. I'm not running—I'm choosing the battlefield.
